## Rules

1. Default every rule to FAIL. Only mark PASS if you can cite the specific line number(s) that
   prove compliance. A PASS without a line reference is an error in your audit.
2. If a rule does not apply to this function, mark it N/A and explain why.
3. If compliance is ambiguous, mark it REVIEW and explain the ambiguity. Do not guess PASS.
4. Cross-reference your RESEARCH from Step 1. If current best practices differ from the
   reference standards, note the discrepancy in a footnote but audit against the reference
   as written. Flag the newer practice so the team can decide whether to update the standard.

## Required checks

- Colon-bound parameters
- PascalCase naming
- Full .NET type names (no accelerators)
- Object types are the MOST appropriate and specific choice (not just a functional generic type like PSObject or Array)
- Single quotes for non-interpolated strings
- $PSItem not $_
- Explicit bool comparisons ($Var -eq $True, not just $Var)
- If conditions are pre-evaluated outside If blocks
- $Null on left side of comparisons
- No positional arguments to cmdlets
- No cmdlet aliases
- Switch parameters correctly handled
- CmdletBinding with all required properties
- OutputType declared
- Comment-based help is complete (Synopsis, Description, Parameter, Example, Outputs, Notes)
- Error handling via New-ErrorRecord or appropriate pattern
- Try/Catch around operations that can fail
- Write-Debug at Begin/Process/End block entry and exit (if blocks are used)
- No variable pollution (no script: or global: scope leaks)
- 96-character line limit
- 2-space indentation (not tabs, not 4-space)
- OTBS brace style
- No commented-out code
- Registry access is read-only (if applicable)

